{
  "texts": [
    "Early farmers intuitively selected plants with desirable traits for cultivation, laying the groundwork for what would become a sophisticated scientific discipline.",
    "The formalization of plant breeding as a scientific endeavor began in the 19 th century with the work of Gregor Mendel, whose experiments with pea plants established the principles of heredity (Yoosefzadeh Najafabadi et al., 2023c).",
    "Mendel's laws provided a foundational framework for understanding how traits are inherited, enabling breeders to predict the outcomes of their breeding activities (Yoosefzadeh Najafabadi et al., 2023c).",
    "Over time, this knowledge facilitated the development of more structured and systematic approaches to plant breeding (Figure 1).",
    "The 20 th century witnessed remarkable advancements in plant breeding driven by the adoption of genetics and biotechnology (Kim et al., 2020)."
  ]
}